  "summary": "At the Weatherby residence, Edith Weatherby discusses her fatigue and feelings of being a burden with Deirdre Henderson. During the conversation, Deirdre accidentally knocks over a bronze statue while rushing to get eggnog. Mr. Weatherby enters and criticizes Deirdre’s clumsiness and the barking of her Siamese dog. When asked about the investigation into Mrs. Upward's death, Edith notes that the police are struggling to identify a motive or a killer. Mr. Weatherby suggests a vagrant might be responsible and advises Deirdre to lock the doors, while Edith mentions that a maid named Mrs. MacKenzie had worked for Mrs. Upward. After Mr. Weatherby leaves, Maud Williams delivers eggnog to Edith, observing her imposing presence.\n\nMeanwhile, an exhausted Hercule Poirot returns to Broadhurst. At the Long Grass Hotel, he observes Robin Upward struggling to write a play. The atmosphere becomes chaotic when Muriel Sampson arrives in a panic, reporting that Johnny has not returned from the post office, and Morley creates a mess while searching for agricultural forms in the lounge. As Poirot begins to methodically tidy the scattered items, he receives a phone call from Inspector Spence. Spence reveals new evidence: a witness from the Broadhurst post office saw a blonde woman, rather than Deirdre Henderson, entering the house on the night of the murder. This information shifts the suspicion back toward either Evelyn Carpenter or Sheila Lund, leaving Poirot stunned.",
